\begin_body

\begin_layout Section*
Installation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply put, to use Quanta, you need to install it.
 The following guide should be able help you in getting Quanta.
 For advanced users and more configuration, you are always welcome to grab
 the source code of Quanta and do literally whatever you want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quanta is written in Python and requires Python.
 Apart from that you need Gtk, nothing more.
 So we directly follow the guidelines required to use Gtk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Python 3.5+
\series default
 If not installed, get the latest version of Python from the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "website"
target "www.python.org"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Gtk 3.0+
\series default
 The latest version of Gtk is recommended.
 You can learn from the Gtk 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "website"
target "www.gtk.org"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 how to install the stable version.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
PyGObject
\series default
 PyGObject provides Python bindings to GI modules (that is Gtk and its friends).
 If it is your first try with Gtk, you may have to install it.
 Directly install it using PIP (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "PyPI website"
target "https://pypi.org/project/PyGObject/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) or follow the instructions from the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "module's website"
target "https://pygobject.readthedocs.io/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Getting Quanta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the requirements are satisfied, installing Quanta won't be a trouble.
 The best way is to install it using PIP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "language=bash"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$ pip install quanta
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As already stated, for those not comfortable with PIP, you can always get
 the source code and do necessary things to get Quanta on your 
\emph on
PYTHONPATH
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
New to Gtk ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It might be case, that you don't even know what is Gtk and perhaps be wondering
 how to get started.
 The following is a quotation from Wikipedia's page for Gtk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
GTK (formerly GTK+ GIMP Toolkit) is a free and open-source cross-platform
 widget toolkit for creating graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
 It is licensed under the terms of the GNU Lesser General Public License,
 allowing both free and proprietary software to use it.
 Along with Qt, it is one of the most popular toolkits for the Wayland and
 X11 windowing systems.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Source"
target "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GTK"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Learning the basics of Gtk will be easy with Python.
 To get familiar with developing Gtk applications, please have a look at
 the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "official docs"
target "https://www.gtk.org/docs/language-bindings/python/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

